'''Justin Lee Pope''' (born November 8, 1979) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]], [[coach (baseball)|coach]], and [[manager (baseball)|manager]]. Pope played [[college baseball]] for the [[University of Central Florida]], where he was a First Team [[All-America]]n.

Drafted by the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], Pope played professionally in [[minor league baseball]] for the Cardinals, [[New York Yankees]], and [[Philadelphia Phillies]] organizations without reaching [[Major League Baseball]]. After ending his playing career, Pope served as a coach in the Yankees farm system. He is currently the manager of the [[Staten Island Yankees]] of the [[New York-Penn League]].

==Career==
===Playing career===
Pope attended [[Wellington High School]] in [[Wellington, Florida]] and the [[University of Central Florida]] (UCF). At UCF, he played [[college baseball]] for the [[UCF Knights baseball]] team, then in the [[Atlantic Sun Conference|Trans America Athletic Conference]] (TAAC).{{ref label|a|a}} At UCF, Pope was named a First Team [[All-American]], TAAC All-Star starting pitcher and TAAC Player of the Year as a junior in 2001. He set the UCF school record for [[strikeout]]s,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/71256012.html?dids=71256012:71256012&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+14%2C+2001&author=&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=UCF%27S+POPE+SETS+RECORD&pqatl=google|title=UCF'S Pope Sets Record|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=April 14, 2001|page=C.5|accessdate=February 14, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=February 2012}}</ref> and pitched 38 consecutive scoreless innings, breaking [[Roger Clemens]]' record of 35.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2001-04-12/sports/0104120217_1_justin-pope-roger-clemens-ucf|title=`Bulldog' Pope Has Ucf Loaded With Rich Pitching: Junior Right-hander Justin Pope Broke Roger Clemens' Scoreless Innings Streak Of 35|date=April 12, 2001|first=Jeff|last=Case|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=February 14, 2012}}</ref>

The [[St. Louis Cardinals]] drafted Pope in the first round (28th overall) of the [[2001 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/73700358.html?dids=73700358:73700358&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+06%2C+2001&author=Alan+Schmadtke%2C+Sentinel+Staff+Writer&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=UCF%27S+POPE+IS+A+1ST-ROUNDER+THE+ST.+LOUIS+CARDINALS+PICKED+JUNIOR+RIGHT-HANDER+JUSTIN+POPE+28TH.&pqatl=google|title=UCF'S Pope is a 1st-Rounder: The St. Louis Cardinals Picked Junior Right-Hander Justin Pope 28th|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|first=Alan|last=Schmadtke|date=June 6, 2001|page=D.5|accessdate=February 14, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=February 2012}}</ref> He made his professional debut with the [[New Jersey Cardinals]] of the Class-A Short Season [[New York-Penn League]] in 2001, pitching to a 2-4 [[win-loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] and a 2.60 [[earned run average]] in 15 [[games started]]. Pope started 12 games for the [[Peoria Chiefs]] of the Class-A [[Midwest League]] in 2002, and was assigned to the [[Palm Beach Cardinals]] of the Class-A Advanced [[Florida State League]] (FSL) in 2003.

The Cardinals traded Pope and [[Ben Julianel]] to the [[New York Yankees]] for [[Sterling Hitchcock]] in August 2003. The Yankees assigned Pope to the [[Tampa Yankees]] of the FSL. With the Yankees organization, Pope was converted into a [[relief pitcher]]. He was promoted to the Class-AA [[Trenton Thunder]] of the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] in 2004. He received promotions to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Class-AAA]] affiliates of the Yankees, the [[Columbus Clippers]] in 2006 and the [[Scranton/Wilkes-Barre Yankees]] in 2007, but was never promoted to [[Major League Baseball]]. Pope signed with the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] as a minor league free agent for the 2008 season. He pitched for the Class-AA [[Reading Phillies]] of the Eastern League, and retired after the season.<ref name=silive/>

===Coaching career===
Pope served as a [[coach (baseball)|coach]] for the [[Staten Island Yankees]] of the New York-Penn League in 2010 and the Trenton Thunder in 2011. He was named manager of Staten Island for the 2012 season.<ref name=silive>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/siyankees/index.ssf/2012/01/justin_pope_tabbed_manager_for.html|newspaper=[[Staten Island Advance]]|title=Justin Pope tabbed manager for Staten Island Yankees|date=January 6, 2012|first=Jim|last=Waggoner|accessdate=February 14, 2012}}</ref>

==Notes==
:{{note label|a|a}} The Trans America Athletic Conference is now known as the [[Atlantic Sun Conference]].

